<HL>
   AT&amp;T Increases
   Rates for Services
   Used by Businesses
   ----
   By John J. Keller
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   T
</CO>
<IN>
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. plans to
increase by the end of the month its charges for several
long-distance communications services to businesses.
   AT&amp;T's price boost, when it becomes effective July 27,
will amount to a 2% overall increase in rates for two
outbound-calling services sold to businesses and a 0.5% boost
in the monthly bill for business customers who use multiple
AT&amp;T services, the company said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   That boost, while small, would be one of the most
significant since the Federal Communications Commission last
year changed its method of regulating the company's profit
from long-distance service.
   The FCC used to make AT&amp;T set its rates according to its
costs of delivering service. Now the commission sets a "price
cap" on what AT&amp;T can charge. The idea is to motivate AT&amp;T to
cut its costs of delivering service, thereby allowing
customers to benefit from lower pricing while AT&amp;T gets to
keep more of what it makes on each call.
   Since late 1989, the company has increased certain flat
fees, such as private-line hookups and consumer calls to AT&amp;T
operators. The latest increase would apply to so-called usage
charges covering the time of day a call is made and the
distance it travels.
   AT&amp;T, which is expected to announce lower second-quarter
earnings later this week, derives more than 50% of its
revenue from long-distance service and, with a more than 65%
share, dominates the U.S. market.
   The company said the price increases will affect about 8%
of its business customers, and are being made to cover
increased costs of installing new digital equipment and
backup systems in its network, inflation and other
unspecified costs.
   "Over the past five years we've lowered {overall
long-distance} prices by 45%. Now we're talking about a 2%
bump," said a company spokeswoman. "It's fine-tuning to
maintain our service {profit} margins."
   AT&amp;T estimated that it has reduced outbound-calling prices
for businesses by 32% since 1984. It said the "price-cap"
formula by which it sets its pricing would be adjusted to
show an additional $46 million in annual revenue this year
compared with 1989, because of the latest pricing change.
   Specifically, pricing increases will apply to a customer's
network usage, including time-of-day charges and the distance
that a call travels between two points, said AT&amp;T. The
affected services are AT&amp;T Software Defined Network Service,
or SDN, and several plans within the AT&amp;T PRO WATS
long-distance service.
   For example, a six-minute call between San Francisco and
Washington using PRO WATS service will increase to $1.52 from
$1.49 today. A five-minute daytime call between Chicago and
Denver over AT&amp;T's SDN network will climb to 97 cents from
the current 95 cents.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading, AT&amp;T closed
at $37.125, unchanged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
