<HL>
   IBM's Profit
   Advanced 5.2%
   In 2nd Period
   ---
   Solid Result Boosts Stocks;
   Problems May Be Ahead
   As Mainframe Sales Fell
   ----
   By Paul B. Carroll
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   IBM
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   International Business Machines Corp. reported a solid
5.2% increase in second-quarter earnings, the first time
since the mid-1980s that the company has put together
respectable quarters back to back.
   "While first-half results are encouraging, much remains to
be done this year," IBM Chairman John Akers said in a
statement that was slightly more measured than the one that
accompanied the first-quarter earnings report.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   IBM did exceed securities analysts' expectations for the
second consecutive quarter, reporting net income of $1.41
billion, or $2.45 a share, while analysts had generally
estimated $2.25 to $2.35 a share. A year earlier, IBM earned
$1.34 billion, or $2.31 a share. (Per-share earnings grew
faster than the total figure because IBM has been buying back
shares, cutting the average number outstanding to 573.3
million from 581.4 million a year earlier.) Revenue climbed a
surprisingly strong 8.4%, to $16.5 billion from $15.21
billion.
   The biggest surprise in the quarter was the strength of
software revenue, which grew 26% to $2.35 billion. Although
software revenue had increased a heady 30% to 35% for years,
growth had recently slowed into the single digits as IBM had
begun providing hefty discounts on software as a way of
increasing hardware sales. IBM indicated that the strong
showing was an aberration but suggested that percentage
increases in the mid-teens were possible in the second half.
   IBM said results continued to be good in personal
computers, where IBM has been gaining market share for the
past year and a half. Demand also remained strong for a line
of high-end disk drives that IBM began shipping late last
year. IBM also singled out for praise the AS/400, a line of
minicomputers that had been going gangbusters since its
introduction two years ago but that had finally seemed to be
losing momentum in the first quarter.
   Revenue rose again in the U.S., even though the whole
computer industry has been having trouble here for years --
although the increase was apparently in the low single
digits, as opposed to the double-digit growth of the first
quarter and the 1989 second quarter.
   IBM also said it is seeing some early benefits from a
job-reduction and plant-consolidation program that occasioned
a $2.4 billion write-off in the 1989 fourth quarter. Benefits
from the program are expected to really start to show up in
the second half.
   At the same time, IBM acknowledged that 20 cents a share
of the latest quarter's earnings came from the drop in the
dollar -- because IBM does nearly 60% of its business
overseas, and a drop increases the value of that business
when it is translated into dollars.
   In addition, operating profit margins were disappointing.
Profit before taxes, interest expense and other income was
just 15.7% of revenue, while many securities analysts had
been predicting the margin would be at least half a
percentage point higher. The difference apparently came
because a heavier-than-expected percentage of revenue came
from products such as personal computers, where profit
margins are lower than on the big systems.
   The decline in mainframe revenue wasn't a big surprise,
given that a manufacturing problem in the 1989 first quarter
packed far more deliveries into last year's second quarter
than are normal. Still, IBM indicated that second-quarter
mainframe revenue was flat compared with this year's first
quarter -- even though the second quarter typically accounts
for 25% of mainframe revenue and the first 15%.
   In the first half, IBM earned $2.45 billion, or $4.26 a
share, up 6.8% from $2.29 billion, or $3.92 a share. Revenue
climbed 9.8% to $30.68 billion from $27.94 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900717-0101
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900717-0101.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   Whose Party Now?
</HL>
<DATE>
07/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<LP>
   The disintegration of the Soviet Communist Party continues
apace. At an ostensibly rebellious Party Congress, Mikhail
Gorbachev arranged to have himself re-elected General
Secretary, and secured a rubber stamp on his plans to reduce
the party's role. Then Boris Yeltsin, president of the
Russian Federation parliament, announced his resignation from
the party and dramatically strode out of the congress.
Gavriil Popov and Anatoly Sobchak, mayors of Moscow and
Leningrad respectively, followed him in resignation, as have
and will many others in the party rank and file. Now some
50,000 people assembled outside the Kremlin in opposition to
the party, and Mr. Gorbachev commanded it to give up its
total control of radio and television.
   The message is reaching even into the U.S. State
Department. Stopping in Ireland on his way to receive a
briefing on the Party Congress from Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze, Secretary of State Baker opined that the U.S.
government might actually start to talk to the likes of
Yeltsin-Popov-Sobchak if they get around to forming an
official opposition party. Maybe State will even succeed in
discovering that these three have all been voted into office
in popular elections, unlike Mr. Gorbachev and other
central-government officials.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Indeed, Mr. Gorbachev's new governmental architecture
raises some interesting questions of political authority.
Chief of State Gorbachev inherits the power taken away from
General Secretary Gorbachev. On paper, President Gorbachev
has far more power. The military and KGB now will report
directly to the president and will be less answerable to the
party. Party cells already are being removed from factories,
putting heads of enterprises directly under presidential
authority.
   Mr. Gorbachev will leave party duties to his
unprepossessing choice for deputy general secretary, Vladimir
Ivashko. The central committee's Politburo, once the supreme
power in the Soviet Union, will become a debating society. It
now will meet only once a month. Mr. Shevardnadze and other
key ministers saw no need to remain members.
   Mikhail Gorbachev has chosen to try to rule the Soviet
Union through the presidency, rather than the party. But now
that he has created a dictatorial presidency, a question
arises: Will anyone do what he dictates? Clearly he has
cleverly positioned himself in anticipation of the party's
rapid decline, leaving open the possibility that he himself
can defect when the time is ripe. But where will he get his
political authority meanwhile?
   He was not elected president by the people, but by a
Supreme Soviet carefully packed with Communists. He is not as
popular with the people as Mr. Yeltsin appears to be,
although Mr. Yeltsin's popularity probably derives more from
his anti-party campaign than from a widespread belief that he
can deliver the people from their misery.
   Mr. Gorbachev still will derive some authority from the
party -- until it withers away. Some will continue to come
from the Supreme Soviet, although this legislative body also
will suffer from the rising public anger at communism. That
will make Mr. Gorbachev more dependent on the military and
the KGB as he tries to maintain public order.
   But the army and quite possibly the KGB as well are
themselves suffering deep inner divisions over who exactly
has authority. Generals of the army by and large supported
Communist hard-liners in the congress, but there is
increasing evidence that the rank and file leans toward the
reformers. Some of the rank and file, of course, come from
secessionist-minded republics and don't like anything
Russian. So when President Gorbachev issues orders, can he be
certain they will be obeyed now that party discipline in
these two powerful institutions has been weakened?
   Some of those thoughts no doubt crossed Mr. Gorbachev's
mind when he watched Mr. Yeltsin walk out. That no doubt
explains why he reacted so bitterly. Perhaps he was tempted
to also shed the party albatross. But that he couldn't do.
Mr. Gorbachev will stay put and will need all his
considerable political skills to withstand the forces of
revolution now raging in the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900717-0100
</DOCNO>
