</DOCID>
<HL>
   SEC Is Assailed
   Over Supervising
   Financial Planners
   ----
   By Kevin G. Salwen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<IN>
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The investigative arm of Congress delivered
a scathing report on the financial-planning industry and
contended that the Securities and Exchange Commission's
oversight "may be doing more harm than good."
   The General Accounting Office study said that investors
may be misled by the SEC's implied "seal of approval" in
licensing financial planners. The process must be improved,
the GAO said, "to provide people who might use an adviser a
minimum level of assurance" that the adviser operates within
the law.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The GAO report focuses on an industry that has more than
tripled over the past decade to about 14,000 registered
advisers who now manage roughly $4.6 trillion in assets. As
its basis, the GAO used figures from other studies showing
that advisers defrauded investors of $90 million to $200
million a year. But the agency added that it thought the
figures were low, and some consumer groups put the annual
figure much higher.
   In a response by Kathryn McGrath, former head of the
investment-management division, the SEC conceded that its
oversight is below par but quickly added that doing more
would require much more money. The report offers "laudable
goals that the staff would support in a cost-free
environment," Ms. McGrath said.
   Last spring, Rep. Rick Boucher (D., Va.) unveiled a bill
that would force all financial planners to register with the
SEC, provide full written disclosure to clients of
compensation and allow customers to sue for damages. As
important, the legislation would give the SEC broader ability
to attack abuse by financial planners, including fining
power.
   Rep. Boucher's bill isn't considered likely to go far this
year, and the first hearing on the matter will be held
tomorrow by the House subcommittee on telecommunications and
finance.
   The Investment Advisers Act of 1940 requires financial
planners to register with the SEC. But the GAO reported that
a financial planners group, the International Association of
Financial Planning, estimated that there are 100,000 to
300,000 financial planners in the U.S.
   Registration doesn't necessarily improve an investor's
chances of getting a competent adviser, the GAO said.
Planners don't need any training, said the GAO, which quoted
one industry official as saying, "It is easier to become a
registered investment adviser than to become a licensed
driver."
   In one example, the GAO described a woman who lost her
life savings of $60,000 despite being "impressed" that the
adviser was SEC-registered.
   Moreover, the report criticized the agency's inspection of
licensed advisers. The SEC usually inspects advisers for the
first time an average of three years after they are
registered, but many have never been inspected, the report
said.
   The SEC has proposed setting up a self-regulatory
organization for financial planners, but that plan hasn't
gone far.
   The GAO recommended that the SEC inspect all newly
registered advisers within a year and periodically afterward.
The SEC called the proposal "a good idea." Advisers shown to
be riskier should have a shorter leash, with inspections
every six months, the GAO said. In addition, the report
proposed that the SEC verify education and other experience
before granting registration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900717-0054
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900717-0054.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   In Japan, Shearson Sells
   American Express Cards
</HL>
<DATE>
07/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   AXP SLH
</CO>
<IN>
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Clients of Shearson Lehman Hutton Asia Inc. are
used to being sold stocks, bonds and financial services. But
the latest product the firm is pushing comes straight from
above: American Express cards.
   Employees of the stockbroking and investment-banking
subsidiary of American Express Co. are soliciting members for
the parent company's credit-card operation in Japan. Instead
of the commissions that brokers are accustomed to earning,
successful card sellers earn prizes like cameras, golf clubs
and bicycles.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Not surprisingly, officials at Shearson and American
Express don't see any conflict between selling stocks and
promoting credit cards. "A lot of these guys are taking this
seriously," says Marc A. Bouchard, chief operating officer at
Shearson Lehman Hutton Asia. Still, he adds, "we're not doing
it professionally. And, actually, most people who are being
asked are suppliers rather than clients. It's less
embarrassing."
   American Express says it routinely asks company employees
to promote its cards in Japan. "Shearson Lehman people are
part of the American Express family," says Yoji Takesaki, a
spokesman for American Express in Japan. "And all American
Express people are responsible for finding as many new
clients as possible." American Express employs 1,239 people
in Japan, including 320 at Shearson Lehman Hutton.
</TEXT>
