<HL>
   Business Brief -- General Development Corp.:
   Developer May Be Forced
   To Pay Out Larger Claims
</HL>
<DATE>
07/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   GDV
</CO>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
</IN>
<LP>
   General Development Corp. said it will probably have to
pay much larger claims than it originally thought for a
revised plea-bargain agreement to settle charges that it
defrauded thousands of home buyers.
   The developer, which is operating under federal bankruptcy
law protection, was dealt a blow last week when a federal
judge rejected its plea-bargain agreement with the U.S.
attorney in Miami. Under the restitution part of that
agreement, General Development would have had to pay home
buyers $80 million to $100 million over 25 years.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   General Development said the court gave the parties until
Aug. 7 to submit a revised plea agreement and restitution
plan. Failing that, the court will set a date to begin the
company's trial. The company, which said it has been
negotiating with the U.S. attorney, said it believes it will
be able to develop a plan by Aug. 7 that will satisfy the
court.
   However, General Development said, "It is likely that the
revised terms of the restitution plan would result in
substantially larger claims for restitution than originally
anticipated."
