<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
07/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   STOCKS SOARED AGAIN with the Dow Jones industrials rising
19.55 points to a record 2999.75, just shy of the 3000 level.
Much of the impetus for the advance came from strong
second-quarter profits for some companies. Bonds were little
changed and the dollar ended mixed.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   IBM earnings climbed 5.2% in the second quarter, the first
time in years that the computer giant has put two respectable
quarters back to back. Revenue rose a strong 8.4%, although
declining in the mainframe sector.
   ---
   McDonnell Douglas will slash 14,000 to 17,000 jobs by the
end of the year to trim costs. The cutbacks by the nation's
largest defense contractor are the largest announced so far
this year by any aerospace company.
   ---
   Columbia S&amp;L's sale of junk bonds was closer to getting
off the ground, with its portfolio attracting bids within 10%
of its $2.9 billion book value, people close to the sale
said.
   ---
   An Ohio judge threw out the bribery case against Rite Aid
Corp. and its president, saying the evidence and testimony
presented during a trial was insufficient to give to a jury.
   ---
   All asbestos claims must be consolidated in a single
court, a judge in Cleveland ordered. The move further
complicates the Manville case and may set off a judicial turf
war.
   ---
   Revco D.S. creditors may have grounds to sue former
shareholders and others responsible for Revco's failed $1.25
billion leveraged buy-out, according to a preliminary report
prepared by a special examiner.
   ---
   Chase Manhattan's earnings fell 62% in the latest quarter,
as problem real estate loans worsened. First Chicago reported
a 35% drop in profit while Bank of New York posted a 39%
decline. Midlantic had a loss.
   ---
   Spending cuts totaling $100 billion will be triggered this
fall unless a deficit-reduction pact is reached, the
administration warned. It said the fiscal 1991 deficit,
excluding the S&amp;L bailout, will soar to $168.8 billion.
   ---
   Ford will boost spending to market its highest-volume cars
and put incentives on the 1991 Ford Escort and Mercury
Tracer. Ford also will invest $80 million in a Hungarian
parts plant.
   ---
   Southland reached an agreement in principle with senior
debtholders and a Japanese suitor, averting the possibility
of bankruptcy proceedings.
   ---
   The Fed plans to relax limits on securities activities by
U.S. banks abroad and broaden the businesses those units can
enter without specific approval from the central bank.
   ---
   The CBOT directed Stotler &amp; Co., the futures brokerage
subsidiary of Stotler Group, to boost its capital by the
close of business tomorrow or begin liquidating customer
accounts.
   ---
   Whitman Corp. is negotiating to sell its Hussman
refrigerator manufacturing unit to Sanyo Electric for $500
million to $600 million, according to people familiar with
the talks.
   ---
   NCR posted a 4.5% rise in second-quarter earnings, citing
strong foreign sales that offset continuing weakness in the
U.S. computer market.
   ---
   RJR's junk bonds soared after the company said it would
retire many of the issues as part of a refinancing.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 149,430,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2999.75, up 19.55; transportation 1189.60, up 2.01; utilities
205.86, off 0.31.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3451.03, up
3.47.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 131.92, off 0.30;
spot index 132.06, off 1.22.
   Dollar: 148.15 yen, unchanged; 1.6547 marks, up 0.0037.
</TEXT>
